SIMPLE: wiredraw
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wiredraw
<hw>Wire"draw`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Wiredrew</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Wiredrawn</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Wiredrawing</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To form (a piece of metal) into wire, by drawing it
through a hole in a plate of steel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to draw by art or violence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My sense has been <qex>wiredrawn</qex> into blasphemy.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, also, to draw or spin out to great length and
tenuity; <as>as, to <ex>wiredraw</ex> an argument</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such twisting, such <qex>wiredrawing</qex>, was never seen in a
court of justice.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Steam Engine)</fld> <def>To pass, or to draw off,
(as steam) through narrow ports, or the like, thus reducing its pressure
or force by friction.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wire-drawer</ent>⟦br⟧
